Participation and Funding for Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP)

SNAP is is a federal program that provides monthly funds for people to buy food. The goal of SNAP is to reduce poverty and food insecurity while stimulating economic growth. SNAP benefits work similar to a debit card where funds are placed on an Electronic Benefit Transfer (EBT) card. Funds are automatically loaded into an account each month and the card can be used to purchase groceries at authorized locations (i.e.Â grocery stores, Walmart, farmers markets).

SNAP is one of the largest program fighting food insecurity in the United States. Overtime the amount of people who qualify and receive SNAP benefits changes. As the amount of people needing these benefits changes so does the amount of funding.
